"1356–Overleden","1358–Female":"1358–Overleden","1363–Male":"1363–Overleden","1311–Male":"1311–Overleden","1313–Female":"1313–Overleden","1363":"1363","Abt 1358":"circa 1358","Abt 1356":"circa 1356","1358":"1358","1313":"1313","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1400":"1400","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1311":"1311","about 1334":"circa 1334","about 1363":"circa 1363","Feliskirk, Yorkshire, England":"Feliskirk, Yorkshire, England","Mildenhall Manor, Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Feliskirk, , Yorkshire, England":"Feliskirk, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1334–":"about 1334–Deceased","1334–Female":"1334–Deceased","1335–1400":"1335–1400","1356–Male":"1356–Deceased","1358–Female":"1358–Deceased","1363–Male":"1363–Deceased","1311–Male":"1311–Deceased","1313–Female":"1313–Deceased","1363":"1363","Abt 1358":"about 1358","Abt 1356":"about 1356","1358":"1358","1313":"1313","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1400":"1400","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1311":"1311","about 1334":"about 1334","about 1363":"about 1363","Feliskirk, Yorkshire, England":"Feliskirk, Yorkshire, England","Mildenhall Manor, Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Feliskirk, , Yorkshire, England":"Feliskirk, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Filliol","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Gaston, Emile, Lucien, Marcel, Aime, Cecile, Donat, Fernand, Gisele, Jean Luc.","French: from Old French <i>fillon</i> ‘little boy’, a diminutive of <i>fils</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used to denote the youngest son of a family. In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the variant   Filion  , which is rare in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Filion","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Denys, Gaetan, Germain, Gilles, Herve, Jacques, Jean-Louis, Joffre, Laurette, Laurier.","French: variant of   Fillion   ‘little boy’.","History: Antoine Filion from Paris, France, married Anne (d’)Anneville in Paris <i>c.</i> 1656, died in Quebec City, QC, <i>c.</i> 1669."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Filliol was born about 1334, in Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Filiol, was 25 and her mother, Mrs. John Filiol, was 23. She married John de Southwell IV. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1334–":"umbes 1334–Surnud","1334–Female":"1334–Surnud","1335–1400":"1335–1400","1356–Male":"1356–Surnud","1358–Female":"1358–Surnud","1363–Male":"1363–Surnud","1311–Male":"1311–Surnud","1313–Female":"1313–Surnud","1363":"1363","Abt 1358":"umbes 1358","Abt 1356":"umbes 1356","1358":"1358","1313":"1313","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1400":"1400","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1311":"1311","about 1334":"umbes 1334","about 1363":"umbes 1363","Feliskirk, Yorkshire, England":"Feliskirk, Yorkshire, England","Mildenhall Manor, Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mil